text: Biosynthesis of Diverse Type II Polyketide Core Structures in Streptomyces coelicolor M1152 Xuechen Zhu,* Vilja Siitonen, Charles E. Melançon III, and Mikko Metsä-Ketelä* ABSTRACT: Synthetic biology-based approaches have been employed to generate advanced natural product (NP) pathway intermediates to overcome obstacles in NP drug discovery and production. Type II polyketides (PK-IIs) comprise a major subclass of NPs that provide attractive structures for antimicrobial and anticancer drug development. Herein, we have assembled ﬁve biosynthetic pathways using a generalized operon design strategy in Streptomyces coelicolor M1152 to allow comparative analysis of metabolite production in an improved heterologous host. The work resulted in production of four distinct PK-II core structures, namely benzoisochromanequinone, angucycline, tetracenomycin, and pentangular compounds, which serve as precursors to diverse pharmaceutically important NPs. Our bottom-up design strategy provided evidence that the biosynthetic pathway of BE-7585A proceeds via an angucycline core structure, instead of rearrangement of an anthracycline aglycone, and led to the discovery of a novel 26-carbon pentangular polyketide. The synthetic biology platform presented here provides an opportunity for further controlled production of diverse PK-IIs in a heterologous host. KEYWORDS: type II polyketides, biosynthesis, bottom-up strategy, Streptomyces, natural products T he emergence of pathogenic microbes and cancer cells the continued deployment of new pharmaceutical countermeas- including polyketides,2−4 ures.1 Natural products (NPs), nonribosomal3 and ribosomal5 peptides, aminoglycosides,6 terpenoids, and others possess a broad range of bioactivities that have made them highly successful in antimicrobial and anticancer drug development. Among these, type II polyketides (PK-IIs)4 are a major subclass of NPs with diverse structures and bioactivities, which include the well-known antibacterial tetracyclines7 and anticancer agent doxorubicin.8

Synthetic biology-based production of advanced natural product pathway intermediates that can be further derivatized synthetically or biosynthetically is an attractive option to meet challenges in NP drug discovery and production;9,10 and to facilitate systematic functional studies of enzymes involved in NP biosynthesis.11 PK-IIs are attractive targets for application of several structurally distinct classes of advanced, stable pathway intermediates termed PK-II core structures can be produced such an approach for several Cite This: ACS Synth. Biol. 2021, 10, 243−251 © 2021 American Chemical Society using relatively small gene cassettes (6−10 genes, ∼5−9 kb), making PK-IIs fairly “genetically economical” compared to other classes of NPs such as type I polyketides12 and nonribosomal peptide.12 This genetic economy oﬀers an accelerated route to operon construction and optimization. Second, a small number of these core structures, in turn, serve as precursors to a much larger number of diversely tailored PK- II ﬁnal products. On the other hand, considering the 76 biosynthetically studied PK-IIs, BIQ, TET, ANT, and ANG subclasses embody 40 of the 45 C9-reduced PK-IIs (89%), while TCM and PEN subclasses embody 27 of the 31 unreduced ones (87%). The fact that common advanced intermediates are employed on numerous diverse pathways makes the biosynthesis of PK-IIs highly amenable to “bottom- up”, synthetic biology-based approaches.

PK-IIs are found almost exclusively in Actinobacteria and share conserved biosynthetic features comprising four phases (Figure 1A): priming, extension, cyclization, and tailoring.4,13 In the priming phase, an acyl starter unita malonyl unit in ∼65% of studied casesis transferred to an acyl carrier protein (ACP) by an acyltransferase (AT) co-opted from fatty acid the heterodimeric biosynthesis. https://dx.doi.org/10.1021/acssynbio.0c00482 ACS Synth. Biol. 2021, 10, 243−251 ketosynthase (KSα/β) enzyme complex catalyzes the transfer of the starter unit from ACP to its own active site, where it is decarboxylated (in the case of a malonyl unit), then undergoes iterative Claisen-like condensations with incoming malonyl- ACPs to generate a poly β-ketone chain with length (16−30 atoms) controlled by the size of the KSα/β active site cavity. In the cyclization phase, the highly reactive poly β-ketone chain may be reduced at C-9 by a ketoreductase (C9KR), and is regiospeciﬁcally cyclized and aromatized by a particular combination of 2 to 4 aromatase/cyclase (AroCyc) and cyclase (Cyc) enzymes to form the PK-II core structure, a speciﬁc aromatic fused ring polyketide intermediate (see Figure 1B for examples). Six common types of PK-II core structures (BIQ, ANT, ANG, TET, TCM, and PEN), as well as several rare types, are known. In the ﬁnal tailoring phase, core structures are modiﬁed in successive steps by a diverse array of oxidative, reductive, and group transfer enzymes to generate the ﬁnal PK-II products.4

Although E. coli is by far the most commonly used host for heterologous expression due to its rapid growth rate and ease of genetic manipulation, the essential PK-II biosynthetic protein complex KSα/β suﬀers from signiﬁcant expression and solubility problems in E. coli.17 Recent work has allowed the discovery of selected KSα/β genes that are compatible for expression in E. coli, and this has enabled the production of BIQ,18 ANG, and 24-carbon polyketides19 in the heterologous host. However, Streptomyces are advantageous for NP discovery and overproduction due to their high yield production in an industrial setting.20 Therefore, model strains of Streptomyces are still the preferred hosts for heterologous expression of PK- II pathways. Core structures, including (S)-DNPA,21 G-2A,16 rabelomycin,22 and auramycinone,23 have been produced in these studies. However, these studies were conducted in diﬀerent hosts using diﬀerent vectors, promoter systems, and operon designs. To date, no single heterologous expression host/vector system has been shown to be generally applicable to producing diverse PK-II core structures. In the present work, we have utilized a single host/vector combination and generalized operon design strategy to produce ﬁve PK-II core structures representing four distinct subclasses (BIQ, ANG, TCM, and PEN). The producer strains developed here are a powerful tool for expanding the scope and increasing the pace of PK-II biosynthesis and bioengineer- ing work. These strains can be used as starting points for systematic coexpression of PK-II tailoring enzymesindivid- ually or in combinationto construct diverse structurally elaborated PK-II-like molecules for bioactivity studies, and to systematically elucidate the functions of PK-II tailoring enzymes and pathways.

We ﬁrst engineered a plasmid developed for Streptomyces to generate the expression vector for PK-II biosynthesis genes. In study,24 a high copy plasmid pSUA5 was a previous constructed to test the expression of wild type humanized enhanced GFP (eGFP) in Streptomyces hosts. The eGFP-His gene was selected for Streptomyces gene cloning were introduced. The original constitutive SF14 promoter was replaced with a natural, self- regulatory PK-II operon promoter PactI.25 Promoter PactI and its activator gene actII-orf426 were ampliﬁed from the actinorhodin cluster contained in Streptomyces coelicolor A3(2) genome. To ensure that the complete actII-orf4 operon was ampliﬁed, a part of the adjacent actII-orf 3 gene sequence27 was included in the amplicon. In the actinorhodin cluster, a removed, and restriction sites sequence length of 179 base pairs resides between PactI and the ribosome binding site (RBS) of the actI-orf1 gene (Figure S1). Aiming at a precise design of the vector, we constructed variant plasmids pXZ3 and pXZ4, either with or without the “junction sequence”, respectively, to investigate its role. The eGFP-His gene24 was cloned into pXZ3 and pXZ4 as a reporter, giving pXZ5′ and pXZ5, respectively (Figure 2A). S.

The eGFP-His protein isolated from Streptomyces host24 was used as the positive control (+). coelicolor M115228 is a genetically engineered Streptomyces coelicolor, secondary in which four active endogenous metabolite gene clusters are deleted from the genome that has been designed for expression of NP biosynthesis genes.28,29 Here, we chose it as the host to test the function of pXZ5′ and pXZ5. Plasmids pXZ4, pXZ5′, and pXZ5 were introduced into S. coelicolor M1152, resulting in the transformant strains M1152::pXZ4, M1152::pXZ5′, and M1152::pXZ5. These strains were grown in tryptic soy broth (TSB) media, and the expression of eGFP-His protein in each strain was assessed using whole-cell ﬂuorescence quantiﬁcation (Figure S2) and anti-His Western blotting (Figure 2B). Our results showed that eGFP-His protein was only expressed in M1152::pXZ5, which highlights the indispensability of the “junction sequence” for the function of PactI. Given this insight, plasmid pXZ4, carrying PactI along with the additional sequence, was used as the expression vector for the PK-II biosynthesis genes.

The minimal PKS, which catalyzes the generation of the poly β-ketone chain, is essential to PK-II biosynthesis. To examine the ability of the host/vector combination to express PK-II biosynthesis genes, a minimal PKS was expressed using pXZ4 in S. coelicolor M1152. (KSβ), and actI-orf 3 (ACP) (Figure 4A) was ampliﬁed from the S. coelicolor A3(2) genome and cloned into pXZ4 to generate pXZ6. Plasmid pXZ6 was introduced into S. coelicolor M1152, resulting in the transformant strain M1152::pXZ6. Both M1152::pXZ6 and M1152::pXZ4 were grown in TSB media. To evaluate the expression of the actinorhodin minimal PKS, the metabolic proﬁles of each strain were characterized. The crude extracts were obtained from each culture medium and analyzed using high-performance liquid chromatography (HPLC). In comparison to M1152::pXZ4, a new metabolite peak was detected in the crude extract of M1152::pXZ6 (Figure 4B). This metabolite was then analyzed using high- resolution mass spectrometry (HRMS), and the mass corresponding to actinorhodin minimal PKS product SEK4 (1 in Figure 3)33 was conﬁrmed (Figure S3). Taken together, these results provided direct evidence that actinorhodin minimal PKS was expressed in M1152::pXZ6.

We then used this host/vector combination to produce the BIQ core structure (S)-DNPA (2 in Figure 3).21 The natural sequence harboring actinorhodin genes actI-orf1 (KSα), actI- orf 2 (KSβ), actI-orf 3 (ACP), actIII (C9KR), actVII (AroCycN1-C), actIV (Cyc5), actVI-orf1 (C3KR), and actVI- orfA (Cyc3) was ampliﬁed from S. coelicolor A3(2) genome in fragments. Amplicons were assembled to generate the (S)- DNPA gene cassette (Figure 4A), which was cloned into pXZ4 to generate pXZ11. This plasmid was introduced into S. coelicolor M1152, and the resulting transformant strain M1152::pXZ11 was grown in TSB medium. The crude extract was obtained and analyzed. A new metabolite (Figure 4C) was shown in the production proﬁle of M1152::pXZ11. This metabolite exhibited the UV−visible spectrum (Figure S4) matching that for 2, and a mass that can be linked to 2 was observed in the HRMS analysis. To produce an adequate amount of compound for structural characterization, we tested three commonly used Streptomyces media: TSB, R5 agar, and R4, in which R4 medium (Figure S5) showed the highest yield. R4 medium was chosen to use for the large-scale culture, achieving a yield of ∼15 mg/L. The compound was isolated and characterized using nuclear magnetic resonance (NMR) and circular dichroism (CD) spectrometry, the values of which are consistent with those previously reported for 2.21,34 Furthermore, the correct stereochemistry of 2 produced by M1152::pXZ11 could be observed in the recent cocrystal structure with the BIQ pathway protein Caci_6494, where the NMR and CD data are shown.35 Our results thus clearly proved the ability of M1152::pXZ11 to produce the BIQ core structure.

After successful production of the BIQ core structure using the combination of S. coelicolor M1152 host and pXZ4 vector, we next sought to develop it further to establish a general approach to biosynthesis of diverse PK-II core structures. In plasmid pXZ11, we have preserved the natural sequence conﬁguration of actinorhodin genes, including RBSs and intergenic sequences, to take advantage of a naturally evolved metabolism balance. This idea was also adopted to generalize the operon design strategy for other PK-II core structures. https://dx.doi.org/10.1021/acssynbio.0c00482 ACS Synth. Biol. 2021, 10, 243−251 Figure 4. Clusters for four PK-IIs possessing distinct core structures were selected. The genes required for each core structure were located in the cluster according to a systematic survey of the experimental literature and homolog analyses. Gene sequences were ampliﬁed, and amplicons were assembled to generate the gene cassettes. The gene cassettes were then cloned into the pXZ4 vector, and the resulting plasmids were introduced into S. coelicolor M1152. The metabolic proﬁles of each trans- formant strain representing four PK-IIs were compared to that of M1152::pXZ4 to identify the production of compounds.

To construct the production plasmid for the ANG core structure, we selected the biosynthesis genes for BE-7585A,36 which is an ANG PK-II compound produced by Amycolatopsis orientalis subsp. vinearia. The ANG skeleton of BE-7585A has been suggested previously36 to be formed via an oxidative ring- opening and rearrangement of an ANT structure (Scheme S1A). Controversially, the BE-7585A cluster harbors biosyn- thesis genes bexA (KSα), bexB (KSβ), bexC (ACP), bexD (C9KR), bexL (AroCycN1-C), and bexF (Cyc1) that could account for the direct formation of the ANG core structure. The gene cassette (Figure 5A) consisting of the PK-II genes was ampliﬁed fro the A. orientalis subsp. vinearia genome and cloned into pXZ4, generating plasmid pBE. The pBE- transformed strain M1152::pBE was grown in R4 medium, and its metabolic proﬁle was characterized, which revealed a new metabolite (Figure 5B) in comparison to M1152::pXZ4. Both the UV−visible spectrum (Figure S6) of this metabolite

and the mass obtained in HRMS analysis (Figure S6) were consistent with that of rabelomycin (3 in Figure 3). The ANG core structure UWM6 is not stable and may spontaneously oxidize to 3 in the absence of tailoring enzymes.22 To identify the structure of the metabolite by NMR, a large-scale culture of M1152::pBE was carried out using R4 medium, and the compound was isolated with a yield of ∼4 mg/L. The NMR data (shown in Methods and Figure S7), in comparison with the published data,30 conﬁrmed that M1152::pBE produces 3 and reinforced previous reports on spontaneous generation of 3 from UWM6 in ANG biosynthesis. On account of the “bottom-up” nature of our operon design strategy, investigating the function of pBE enabled us to conﬁrm that BE-7585A is biosynthesized via a typical ANG core structure (Scheme S1B) rather than the rearrangement of an ANT core structure. We next constructed the plasmids for PEN PK-IIs, which can be further classiﬁed into 24-carbon and 26-carbon based on the length of the poly β-ketone chain generated in the extension phase. Frankiamicin produced by Frankia sp. EAN1pec is a 24- carbon PEN PK-II compound.13 To produce the 24-carbon PEN core structure G-2A (4 in Figure 3),16 a gene cassette (Figure 5A) was generated by assembling amplicons of frankiamicin genes f kmA (KSα), f kmB (KSβ), f kmC (ACP), f kmC1 (AroCycN2), f kmC3 (Cyc1pen), f kmC2 (Cyc2), f kmO1 (MOX1), f kmO2 (MOX2), and f kmD (pen19KR), and cloned into the pXZ4 vector, generating pFkm. A new metabolite was detected (Figure 5B), which displayed a typical PEN UV− visible spectrum with an absorption at ∼450 nm (Figure S8). The observation of a [M-H]− peak at 431 in the HRMS spectrum (Figure S8) further supported the production of the 24-carbon PEN core structure. The gene cassette for the 26-carbon PEN PK-II core structure (Figure 5A) was assembled from amplicons of rubromycin genes rubA (KSα), rubB (KSβ), rubC (ACP), rubF (AroCycN2), rubD (Cyc2), rubE (Cyc1pen), rubH (MOX1), https://dx.doi.org/10.1021/acssynbio.0c00482 ACS Synth. rubT (MOX2), and rubG (pen19KR) ampliﬁed from the rubromycin cluster contained in the Streptomyces collinus genome.37,38 Plasmid pRub carrying this gene cassette was constructed and introduced into S. coelicolor M1152, resulting in M1152::pRub. While several 26-carbon PEN PK-IIs have been reported, the core structure for this PEN subclass has not yet been experimentally elucidated. Therefore, only the essential genes for production of the 26-carbon PEN PK-II core structure were chosen to be included in the gene cassette. The strain M1152::pRub was cultivated in R4 medium, and the metabolic proﬁle was analyzed (Figure 5B). A metabolite showing a typical UV−visible spectrum for the PEN structure (Figure S10) was observed. The mass, which could be assigned to a 26-carbon molecule C26H17O9, was found in HRMS analysis (Figure S10). To elucidate the structure by NMR, the compound was produced in a large-scale culture of M1152::pRub and was isolated with a yield of 0.3 mg/L. The NMR data (shown in Methods and Figure S11) revealed that the strain produced a new 26-carbon PEN PK-II compound (5 in Figure 3) that was denoted Rub Z. The new compound possesses an identical carbon scaﬀold to the 24-carbon PEN core structure 4 but has an additional acetyl unit attached, which is generated in an additional KSα/β extension phase that incorporates the twelfth malonyl unit (Scheme S2). To the best of our knowledge, 5 is a novel polyketide, and our bottom-up strategy suggests that it is likely to be the core structure for 26-carbon PEN PK-IIs.

For production of the TCM core structure, we ampliﬁed the sequence carrying genes tcmK (KSα), tcmM (ACP), tcmN (AroCycN2), tcmJ (Cyc2), and tcmI (Cyc1) from the Streptomyces glaucescens genome32 to generate the plasmid pTcm (Figure 5A). The transformant strain M1152::pTcm was grown in R4 medium, and the production of a new metabolite was detected in metabolic proﬁling (Figure 5B). The metabolite was isolated from the large-scale culture of M1152::pTcm with a yield of ∼6 mg/L. The UV− visible spectrum (Figure S12) and HRMS analysis (Figure S12), together with NMR data obtained from the isolated metabolite (shown in Methods and Figure S13), conﬁrmed it is Tcm D3 (6a in Figure 3),31,32 the oxidized form of the TCM core structure. To explore if the oxidation could be prevented in other culture media, the strain M1152::pTcm was grown in soybean meal (SM) medium, and its metabolic proﬁle was characterized. We observed a new metabolite peak in the HPLC spectrum (Figure 5C) with an UV−visible spectrum (Figure S14) and molecular formula (Figure S14) consistent with that of 9-decarboxy-Tcm F1 (6b in Figure 3).32 A large- scale culture of M1152::pTcm using SM medium was carried out to produce the compound for structural elucidation with a yield of ∼2.5 mg/L. The NMR data (shown in Methods and Figure S15) demonstrated that the compound was indeed 6b, which has been proposed as the pH-dependent core structure for the TCM subclass.32 Our results thus validated the ability of M1152::pTcm to be a functional producer of the TCM core structure.

In summary, we have generated gene cassettes for ﬁve PK-II core structures representing four distinct subclasses in a “bottom-up” manner where only the genes required for the biosynthesis of each PK-II core structure were included. Importantly, we adopted a strategy where the natural sequence conﬁgurations of the PK-II biosynthesis genes are preserved in the operon design. Early intermediates in PK-II biosynthesis are exceedingly reactive and susceptible to formation of shunt products.4 We surmised that conservation of natural RBSs would guarantee production of the biosynthetic enzymes in the correct ratio (particularly KSα/KSβ versus Cyc proteins), which would result in clean production proﬁles of the desired metabolites. The “bottom-up” nature of this approach has enabled us to address controversial or inconclusive issues in previous studies. First, we have shown that rabelomycin (3) was produced by expressing selected BE-7585A genes, demonstrating that the biosynthesis of BE-7585A is via a typical ANG pathway, but not rearrangement of an ANT structure. Second, Rub Z (5) was produced, time, by expressing selected rubromycin genes. We infer that this compound is the core structure for 26-carbon PEN PK-IIs, though further bio- conversion experiments with 5, and a PKS mutant of the rubromycin pathway are required to conclusively verify the issue.

All gene cassettes were examined using the pXZ4 vector in the S. coelicolor M1152 host. The pXZ4 vector developed in our study harbors six unique restriction sites, which are rarely present in Streptomyces PK-II genes, making it a user-friendly tool for other Streptomyces PK-II biosynthesis studies. Only three of those restriction sites have been used in the construction of PK-II core structure production plasmids, leaving these plasmids open to further genetic engineering. The successful production of ﬁve PK-II core structures has clearly demonstrated the generality of our approach. Overall, the host/vector combination, production plasmids, and producer strains, will provide a convenient platform for other PK-II biosynthesis studies, such as characterizations of tailoring enzymes and bioengineers that aim to diversify PK-II core structures for generation of novel or improved bioactive molecules. Bacterial Strains and General DNA Techniques. Routine DNA cloning and manipulation were performed using E. coli DH5α strain. Plasmids were passed through E. coli ET12567 to generate the nonmethylated DNA for Streptomyces transformation. S. coelicolor M1152 was used as the host for expression of PK-II biosynthesis genes. Genomic DNAs were extracted from Streptomyces coelicolor A3(2), Amycolatopsis orientalis subsp. vinearia BA-07585, Frankia sp. EAN1pec, Streptomyces collinus, and Streptomyces glaucescens, and served as the templates in PCR ampliﬁcations. Culture conditions and details of the cloning steps are provided in the Supporting Information. Analysis of Proteins and Metabolites. The eGFP-His protein was puriﬁed by Ni-NTA aﬃnity chromatography for anti-His Western blotting analysis. The metabolites were extracted from each bacterial culture medium with ethyl acetate under the acidic condition. The crude extracts obtained after evaporating the organic solvent were dissolved in 50% acetonitrile for HPLC analysis. A detailed description is presented in the Supporting Information.

Mass Spectrometry and NMR Analysis. HRMS (ESI) data were collected in methanol.
